               . I have companions and councellours. And in truth it is very marveilous to some, that this learned Person, who hath manifested so great a tendernesse on his own behalfe, as to call their books monsters, and themselves lyars, who charged his opinion about justification with a Coincidence with that of the Papists, should himselfe so freely impute Antinomianisme to others, an opinion which he esteemes as bad, if not every way worse then that of the Papists about justification; but contenti simus hoc Catone; which is all I shall say, though some would adde;
